value.value: Epileptiform activity refers to distinctive EEG waves or complexes distinguished from background activity found in in a proportion of human subjects with epilepsy, but which can also be found in subjects without seizures. Interictal epileptiform activity refers to such activity that occurs in the absence of a clinical or subclinical seizure.

definition.value: Epileptiform EEG discharges include small sharp spikes (SSSs), wicket spikes, 14- and 6-Hz positive spikes, phantom spike and waves, psychomotor variant, subclinical rhythmic EEG discharges of adults (SREDA), and midline theta rhythm.

value.value: EEG discharges recorded on the entire scalp typically seen in persons with epilepsy.

definition.value: Spikes (<70 ms) and sharp waves (70-200 ms) are sharp transient waves that have a strong association with epilepsy. No difference is noted in terms of clinical significance of spikes and sharp waves. Significant spikes usually are followed by a slow wave.

value.value: EEG with abnormally slow frequencies.
Forward prominence of the entire forehead, due to protrusion of the frontal bone.

definition.value: Not to be confused with frontal bossing.

value.value: An abnormal elevation of the C-reactive protein level in the blood circulation.

definition.value: C-reactive protein (CRP) is produced by the liver, and increases in concentration in response to inflammation.

value.value: Regional increase in the width (height) of the eyebrow.

definition.value: Broadening or flaring can be medial or lateral. Flaring is used to describe a widening with a change in direction of the eyebrow hairs.

label.value: Abnormality of the urinary system physiology

value.value: A morphological abnormality of a digit, i.e., of a finger or toe.
A soft tissue prominence of the ventral aspects of the fingertips or toe tips.

definition.value: The prominence of the finger or toe pads varies throughout life, being greater in neonates and dependent on the state of hydration. This term should not be used if the digit has clubbing. Note that the synonym "fetal fingertip pads" should not be interpreted to mean that the prominent pad necessarily was present in this individual since fetal life. We do not endorse the use of the term "Persistent fetal pads" as this term implies knowledge of the natural history of this finding, which may or may not be known.

value.value: Extension of the proximal transverse crease (five finger crease) to the ulnar edge of the palm.

definition.value: The proximal transverse (five finger) crease starts on the radial side of the hand near the base of the index finger and extends toward the ulnar side of the palm, but does not reach the ulnar side. In this finding, the crease extends completely to the ulnar margin of the palm.

value.value: An abnormality of size or shape of the long bones.
An abnormality of the outline, configuration, or contour of the mouth.
Increased width of the upper lip.
A mild delay in the achievement of motor or mental milestones in the domains of development of a child.
A moderate delay in the achievement of motor or mental milestones in the domains of development of a child.
A severe delay in the achievement of motor or mental milestones in the domains of development of a child.
Thickening of the epidermal layer of the skin.
An abnormality of the morphology of the semicircular canal.
Increased size of the vestibular aqueduct.

definition.value: Enlarged vestibular aqueduct is commonly seen in Pendred syndrome.

value.value: Delivery of newborn by means of a ventouse, a vacuum device used to assist the delivery of a baby when the second stage of labor has not progressed adequately.
A medical history of exposure of the mother of a child or fetus to a teratogenic substance during pregnancy.

definition.value: Commonly encountered maternal teratogens include alcohol, antiepileptic drugs, antihypertensive and antithyroid medications, aspirin, bisphosphonates, chemotherapy, monoclonal antibodies, ionizing radiation, recreational drugs, and serotonin-specific reuptake inhibitors (a class of antidepressants).

value.value: An anomaly of the control or production of movement in the central nervous system.

definition.value: This includes abnormalities in speech, mood, emotions, behavior, and cognition.

value.value: Head circumference below 2 standard deviations below the mean for age and gender at birth.

definition.value: A subjective manifestation of disease localized to the abdomen.

value.value: Onset of disease at the age of between 1 and 5 years.

definition.value: This term refers to ages up to but not including the fifth birthday (see Juvenile onset).

value.value: Feeding problem necessitating gastrostomy tube feeding.

definition.value: This is an extremely severe form of feeding problems in infancy.

value.value: Sensorineural hearing impairment with childhood onset.
Complete loss of hearing related to a sensorineural defect.

label.value: Anterior synechiae of the anterior chamber

value.value: Adhesions between the iris and the cornea.
Generalized reduced transparency of the stroma of the cornea.
Abnormal dilatation of the iris.
Progressive maculopathy characterized by concentric regions of hyper- and hypo-pigmentation.

The condition in which both atria are joined to the left ventricle each by its own atrioventricular valve. Usually there is a hypoplastic right ventricle, which may be on the opposite side of the heart as usual.
Complete absence of the interatrial septum with common atrioventricular valve and two atrioventricular connections.

A conenital abnormality of the aortic arch in which the two embryonic aortc arches form a vascular ring that surrounds the trachea or esophagus and then join to form the descending aorta. Double aortic arch can cause symptoms because of compression of the esophagus (dysphagia, cyanosis while eating) or trachea (stridor).
Non-continuity of the arch of aorta with an atretic point or absent segment.
Right pulmonary venous return to the inferior vena cava.

label.value: Tetralogy of Fallot with absent pulmonary valve

value.value: Features of tetralogy of Fallot with either rudimentary ridges or the complete absence of pulmonic valve tissue.

Any cardiac rhythm other than the normal sinus rhythm. Such a rhythm may be either of sinus or ectopic origin and either regular or irregular. An arrhythmia may be due to a disturbance in impulse formation or conduction or both.
Delay of conduction through the atrioventricular node, which is manifested as prolongation of the PR interval in the electrocardiogram (EKG). All atrial impulses reach the ventricles.

definition.value: The conduction of the cardiac impulse through the atrioventricular node is manifested in the EKG by the PR interval, which is normally less that 200 milliseconds in adults. Normal values are age-dependent in children, but normal values are less that 160 milliseconds in young children.

value.value: An intermittent atrioventricular block with failure of some atrial impulses to conduct to the ventricles, i.e., some but not all atrial impulses are conducted through the atrioventricular node and trigger ventricular contraction.

A conduction block of the right branch of the bundle of His. This manifests as a prolongation of the QRS complex (greater than 0.12 s) with delayed activation of the right ventricle and terminal delay on the EKG.
A conduction block of the left branch of the bundle of His. This manifests as a generalized disturbance of QRS morphology on EKG.
An abnormality of the pulmonary veins.

definition.value: The right superior, right inferior, left superior, and left inferior pulmonary veins carry oxygenated blood to the left atrium.

value.value: A form of hyperaldosteronism caused by a defect within the adrenal gland.
